'''Archer Glacier''' ({{Coord|65|10|S|63|5|W|display=inline,title}}) is a [[glacier]] flowing northwest into the head of [[Bolson Cove]], [[Flandres Bay]], on the west coast of [[Graham Land]]. It was first charted by the [[Belgian Antarctic Expedition]] under [[Adrien de Gerlache]], 1897&ndash;99, and named by the [[United Kingdom Antarctic Place-Names Committee]] in 1960 for [[Frederick Scott Archer]], an [[England|English]] architect who in 1849 invented the wet [[collodion process]] of photography, the first practical process on glass.
