'''''Quintessence: The Search for Missing Mass in the Universe''''' is the fifth non-fiction book by the American theoretical physicist [[Lawrence M. Krauss]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://krauss.faculty.asu.edu/books/quintessence-the-mystery-of-the-missing-mass/|publisher=[[asu.edu]]|title=Quintessence: The Search for Missing Mass in the Universe|accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref> The book was published by [[Basic Books]] on December 21, 2000.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.amazon.com/dp/0465037410|publisher=[[amazon.com]]|title = Quintessence: The Search for Missing Mass in the Universe|accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/100645.Quintessence?from_search=true&search_version=service|publisher=[[goodreads.com]]|title=Quintessence: The Search for Missing Mass in the Universe by Lawrence M. Krauss|accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alternative-thinking.com/catalog/4968298/quintessence-the-search-for-missing-mass-in-the-universe-revised|publisher=alternative-thinking.com | title=Quintessence the Search for Missing Mass in the Universe (Revised) | accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref> This text is an update of his 1989 book ''[[The Fifth Essence]]''. It was retitled ''Quintessence'' after the now widely accepted term for [[Quintessence (physics)|dark energy]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thepg7.com/origins.html | publisher=thepg7.com | title=Origins of the Universe | accessdate=2015-07-24}}</ref>
==Overview== Krauss focuses on [[theoretical physics]] and has published researches on a number of topics within that field. His primary contribution is to [[cosmology]] as one of the first physicists to suggest that most of the [[Mass–energy equivalence|mass and energy]] of the universe resides in empty space, an idea now widely known as "[[dark energy]]". Furthermore, Krauss has formulated a model in which the universe could have potentially come from "nothing," as outlined in his later book ''[[A Universe from Nothing]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/03/25/books/review/a-universe-from-nothing-by-lawrence-m-krauss.html|title=On the Origin of Everything|date=25 March 2012|work=The New York Times}}</ref><ref name=autogenerated1>{{cite web |last=Boutin |first=Paul |title=Theory of Anything? Physicist Lawrence Krauss Takes on His Own |url=http://www.slate.com/id/2131014/|publisher=Slate |accessdate=July 27, 2015 |date=November 23, 2005}}</ref>
Whether our universe is ever-expanding depends on the amount and properties of matter, but there is too little visible matter around us to explain the behavior we can see—over 90% of the universe consists of the missing mass or dark matter,<ref name="dreyfus">{{cite web |title=Questions That Plague Physics: Lawrence Krauss Speaks About Unfinished Business |url=http://www.cwru.edu/artsci/sa_krauss.pdf |publisher=Scientific American |accessdate=July 27, 2015 |author=Dreyfus, Claudia |date=August 2004}}</ref> which Krauss termed "the fifth essence." In this book Krauss demonstrates how the dark matter problem is now connected with two widely discussed areas in the modern cosmology: the [[ultimate fate of the universe]] and the [[cosmological constant]]. He also discusses an [[antigravity|antigravity force]] that may explain recent observations of a permanently expanding universe.
